  "texts": [
    "The first step in self-supervised learning (pretraining on unlabeled data) is called the pretext.",
    "The second step (finetuning the pretrained models on annotated data) is called downstream.The main goal of this research is to use Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs) in a self-supervised learning framework (Fig. 1) to pretrain models on large unlabeled EM datasets and use the weights to fine-tune DL models for various supervised downstream tasks such as semantic segmentation of nanoparticles, denoising, super-resolution, and noise & background removal in high-resolution TEM images.",
    "We show that such pretraining generalizes well and results in faster convergence and improved performance for different kinds of supervised tasks in EM with limited annotated data.",
    "Additionally, pretraining alleviates the need for training complex network architectures and expensive hyperparameter optimization.",
    "As a benchmark, results are compared with the work of Sytwu et al., which investigates the impact of receptive field size on the performance of DL models for semantic segmentation of nanoparticles in TEM images."
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}